WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.840
The when-to-go A wealthy man wanted to go hunting in a part of Northern Canada where

00:06.840 --> 00:10.000
few people had ever hunted.

00:10.000 --> 00:13.720
He traveled to a trading post and tried to find a guy to take him.

00:13.720 --> 00:14.720
But no one would do it.

00:14.720 --> 00:17.280
It was too dangerous, they said.

00:17.280 --> 00:23.000
Finally, he found an Indian who needed money badly, and he agreed to take him.

00:23.000 --> 00:27.360
The Indian's name was Defago.

00:27.360 --> 00:30.800
They made camp in the snow near a large frozen lake.

00:30.800 --> 00:35.960
For three days they hunted, but they had nothing to show for it.

00:35.960 --> 00:40.080
The third night, a windstorm came up.

00:40.080 --> 00:45.600
They lay on their tent listening to the wind howling and the trees whipping back and forth.

00:45.600 --> 00:49.240
To see the storm better, the hunter opened the tent flap.

00:49.240 --> 00:52.160
What he saw started him.

00:52.160 --> 00:58.160
There wasn't a breath of air stirring and the trees were standing perfectly still.

00:58.160 --> 01:03.160
Yet he could hear the wind howling.

01:03.160 --> 01:16.040
And the more he listened, the more it sounded as if it were calling Defago's name.

01:16.040 --> 01:20.480
I must be losing my mind there, Hunter thought.

01:20.480 --> 01:24.200
But Defago had gotten out of his sleeping bag.

01:24.200 --> 01:28.080
He was huddled in a corner of the tent, his head buried in his arms.

01:28.080 --> 01:31.560
What's this all about, the hunter said?

01:31.560 --> 01:36.400
It's nothing, Defago said.

01:36.400 --> 01:48.920
But the wind continued to call to him, and Defago became more tense and more restless.

01:48.920 --> 01:53.880
Eventually he jumped to his feet and he began to run from the tent.

01:53.880 --> 01:56.160
But the hunter grabbed him and wrestled him to the ground.

01:56.160 --> 02:00.480
You can't leave me out here, the hunter shouted.

02:00.480 --> 02:07.320
Then the wind called again and Defago broke loose and ran into the darkness.

02:07.320 --> 02:09.800
The hunter could hear him screaming as he went.

02:09.800 --> 02:15.880
Again and again he cried, oh my fiery feet, my burning feet of fire.

02:15.880 --> 02:23.480
His voice faded away and the wind died down.

02:23.480 --> 02:27.920
At daybreak the hunter followed Defago's tracks in the snow.

02:27.920 --> 02:33.800
They went through the woods, down toward the lake, then out onto the ice.

02:33.800 --> 02:36.480
But soon he noticed something strange.

02:36.480 --> 02:40.840
The steps Defago had taken got longer and longer.

02:40.840 --> 02:44.480
They were so long no human being could have taken them.

02:44.480 --> 02:49.240
It was as if something had helped him to hurry away.

02:49.240 --> 02:55.880
The hunter followed the tracks out to the middle of the lake, but there they disappeared.

02:55.880 --> 03:01.000
At first he thought Defago had fallen through the ice, but there wasn't any hole.

03:01.000 --> 03:07.440
Then he thought something had pulled him off the ice into the sky, but that made no sense.

03:07.440 --> 03:12.760
As he stood wondering what had happened, the wind picked up again.

03:12.760 --> 03:16.480
Then it was howling as it had the night before.

03:16.480 --> 03:18.640
Then he heard Defago's voice.

03:18.640 --> 03:20.680
It was coming from up above.

03:20.680 --> 03:27.400
And again he heard Defago screaming, my fiery feet, my burning feet.

03:27.400 --> 03:31.760
But there was nothing to be seen.

03:31.760 --> 03:35.520
Now the hunter wanted to leave that place as fast as he could.

03:35.520 --> 03:38.520
He went back to camp and packed.

03:38.520 --> 03:43.120
Then he left some food for Defago and he started out.

03:43.120 --> 03:47.080
Weeks later he reached civilization.

03:47.080 --> 03:51.000
The following year he went back to hunt in that area again.

03:51.000 --> 03:54.320
He went to the same trading post to look for a guide.

03:54.320 --> 03:58.360
The people there could not explain what had happened to Defago that night, but they had

03:58.360 --> 04:01.960
not seen him since then.

04:01.960 --> 04:06.720
Maybe it was the windigo, one of them said, and he laughed.

04:06.720 --> 04:09.520
It's supposed to come up with the wind.

04:09.520 --> 04:14.320
It drags you along at great speed until your feet are burned away and more of you than that.

04:14.320 --> 04:17.080
Then it carries you into the sky and it drops you.

04:17.080 --> 04:22.120
It's just a crazy story, but that's what some of the Indians say.

04:22.120 --> 04:26.120
A few days later the hunter was at the trading post again.

04:26.120 --> 04:28.320
An Indian came in and sat by the fire.

04:28.320 --> 04:32.640
He had a blanket wrapped around him and he wore his hat so that you couldn't see his

04:32.640 --> 04:34.680
face.

04:34.680 --> 04:38.480
The hunter thought there was something familiar about him.

04:38.480 --> 04:43.640
He walked over and he asked, are you Defago?

04:43.640 --> 04:47.200
The Indian didn't answer.

04:47.200 --> 04:50.600
Do you know anything about him?

04:50.600 --> 04:53.520
No answer.

04:53.520 --> 04:59.120
He began to wonder if something was wrong, if the man needed help, but he couldn't see

04:59.120 --> 05:00.680
his face.

05:01.680 --> 05:04.680
Are you all right he asked?

05:04.680 --> 05:08.760
No answer.

05:08.760 --> 05:13.600
To get a look at him, he lifted the Indian's hat.

05:13.600 --> 05:24.560
Then he screamed, there was nothing under the hat but a pile of ashes.

05:25.560 --> 05:31.280
Some people say a man is made out of mud.

05:31.280 --> 05:38.440
A poor man's made out of mussel and blood, mussel and blood and skin and bones, a mind

05:38.440 --> 05:44.200
that's weak and a back that's strong, you load sixteen tons, what are you getting?

05:44.200 --> 05:50.400
Another day older and deeper and dead, the same Peter don't you call me cause I can't

05:50.400 --> 05:51.400
go.

05:51.400 --> 05:58.920
So am I so to the company store.

05:58.920 --> 06:01.920
Such things happen.

06:01.920 --> 06:10.440
When Bill Nilsen's cow stopped giving milk, he called the veterinarian, there's nothing

06:10.440 --> 06:18.480
wrong with that cow, the vet said, she's just stubborn, that or some witch got hold of her,

06:18.480 --> 06:21.560
Bill and the vet both laughed.

06:21.560 --> 06:25.760
That old hag, Addy Fitch, I guess she's the closest we've got to a witch around here,

06:25.760 --> 06:31.800
the vet said, but witches have gone out of style, haven't they?

06:31.800 --> 06:35.760
Bill had had a running with Addy Fitch the month before.

06:35.760 --> 06:39.480
He had hit her cat with his car and killed it.

06:39.480 --> 06:45.640
I'm really sorry Addy Fitch, he told her.

06:46.000 --> 06:50.920
I'll get you a new cat, just as pretty, just as good.

06:50.920 --> 06:53.600
Her eyes filled with hate.

06:53.600 --> 06:57.080
I raised that cat from a kitten, she hissed.

06:57.080 --> 07:02.440
I loved her, you'll be sorry for this Bill Nilsen.

07:02.440 --> 07:07.160
Bill sent her a new cat and heard nothing more.

07:07.160 --> 07:10.960
Then, his cow stopped giving milk.

07:10.960 --> 07:14.760
Next, his old truck broke down.

07:14.840 --> 07:19.440
After that, his wife fell and broke her arm.

07:19.440 --> 07:22.040
We're having a lot of bad luck, he thought.

07:22.040 --> 07:25.920
Then he thought, maybe it's Addy Fitch getting even.

07:25.920 --> 07:32.360
And then, hey, you don't believe in witches, you're just upset.

07:32.360 --> 07:35.200
But Bill's grandpa believed in witches.

07:35.200 --> 07:41.000
He had once told Bill that there was only one sure way to stop a witch from causing trouble.

07:41.000 --> 07:44.000
You find a black walnut tree, he said.

07:44.000 --> 07:49.840
And you draw a picture on it, then you mark an X where her heart is, and you drive a nail

07:49.840 --> 07:52.280
into the X.

07:52.280 --> 07:56.280
Every day you drive it in a little deeper.

07:56.280 --> 08:00.320
If she's causing the trouble, he said, she'll feel the pain.

08:00.320 --> 08:04.560
When she can't stand it anymore, she'll come to you or send somebody and try to borrow

08:04.560 --> 08:06.600
something.

08:06.600 --> 08:11.800
If you give her what she wants, that breaks the power of the nail and she'll go on tormenting

08:11.800 --> 08:12.800
you.

08:12.800 --> 08:20.400
But if you don't, she'll have to stop, or the pain will kill her.

08:20.400 --> 08:25.680
That's what his nice gentle old grandpa believed, his pure craziness Bill thought.

08:25.680 --> 08:29.160
Of course, his grandpa didn't have much schooling.

08:29.160 --> 08:33.040
Bill had been to college, and he knew better.

08:33.040 --> 08:41.680
When Bill's dog Joe, a perfectly healthy dog, dropped dead, just like that.

08:41.680 --> 08:43.840
It made Bill angry.

08:43.840 --> 08:51.240
Despite all his schooling, he thought, maybe it is Addy Fitch after all.

08:51.240 --> 09:00.080
He got a red crayon from his son's room, and a hammer, and a nail, and went into the woods.

09:00.080 --> 09:05.920
He found a black walnut tree, and drew a picture of Addy Fitch on it.

09:05.920 --> 09:13.000
He marked an X where her heart was, like his grandpa had said to do.

09:13.000 --> 09:17.920
With the hammer, he drove the nail a little way into the X. Then he went home.

09:17.920 --> 09:20.600
I feel like a fool, he told his wife.

09:20.600 --> 09:23.800
You should, she said.

09:23.800 --> 09:26.960
The next day, a boy named Timmy Logan came by.

09:27.200 --> 09:31.360
Addy Fitch isn't feeling well, he said.

09:31.360 --> 09:36.360
She wonders if she could borrow some sugar from you.

09:36.360 --> 09:40.040
Bill Nelson stared at Timmy in amazement.

09:40.040 --> 09:43.680
He took a deep breath.

09:43.680 --> 09:50.480
Tell her I'm sorry, but I don't have any sugar right now, he said.

09:50.480 --> 09:59.760
When Timmy Logan left, Bill went back to the walnut tree and drove the nail in another inch.

09:59.760 --> 10:02.840
The next day, the boy came back.

10:02.840 --> 10:06.480
Addy Fitch is pretty sick, he said.

10:06.480 --> 10:10.760
She's wondering if you've got any sugar yet.

10:10.760 --> 10:16.400
Tell her I'm sorry Bill Nelson said, but I still don't have any.

10:16.480 --> 10:23.760
Bill went out into the woods and drove the nail in another inch.

10:23.760 --> 10:27.160
The following day, the boy was back.

10:27.160 --> 10:29.440
Addy Fitch is getting sicker, he said.

10:29.440 --> 10:32.520
She really needs some sugar.

10:32.520 --> 10:37.240
Tell her I still don't have any, Bill answered.

10:37.240 --> 10:39.200
Bill's wife was angry.

10:39.200 --> 10:41.800
You've got to stop this, she said.

10:41.800 --> 10:46.320
If this mumbo jumbo works, it's like murder.

10:46.320 --> 10:50.240
I'll stop when she does, he said.

10:50.240 --> 10:54.600
Toward dusk, he stood in the yard staring at the ridge where the old lady lived.

10:54.600 --> 10:58.000
Wondering what was going on up there.

10:58.000 --> 11:03.920
Then in the half-darners, he saw Addy Fitch coming slowly down the hill toward him.

11:03.920 --> 11:09.400
With her pinched bony face and her old black coat, she did look like a witch.

11:09.400 --> 11:15.040
As she got closer, Bill saw that she could hardly walk.

11:15.040 --> 11:18.560
Maybe I'm really hurting her, he thought.

11:18.560 --> 11:23.120
He ran to get his hammer to pull the nail out, but before he could leave, Addy Fitch was

11:23.120 --> 11:26.360
in the yard, her face twisted with rage.

11:26.360 --> 11:31.360
First, you killed my cat, she said.

11:31.360 --> 11:34.640
Then you wouldn't give me a bit of sugar when I needed it.

11:34.640 --> 11:43.240
She swore at him and fell dead at his feet.

11:43.240 --> 11:47.720
I'm not surprised that she dropped dead that way, the doctor said later.

11:47.720 --> 11:52.800
She was very old, maybe 90, it was her heart of course.

11:52.800 --> 11:55.200
Some people thought she was a witch, Bill said.

11:55.200 --> 11:58.840
I've heard that, the doctor said.

11:58.840 --> 12:02.640
Somebody I know thought Addy Fitch had wished him, Bill went on.

12:02.640 --> 12:07.200
He drew a picture of her on a tree, then drove a nail into it to make her stop.

12:07.200 --> 12:10.840
That's all superstition, the doctor said.

12:10.840 --> 12:17.840
But people like us don't believe in that sort of thing, do we?

12:40.840 --> 12:54.560
Is something wrong?

12:54.560 --> 13:00.400
A car broke down late at night way out in the country.

13:00.400 --> 13:03.680
The driver remembered passing an empty house a few minutes earlier.

13:03.680 --> 13:05.880
I'll stay there, he thought.

13:05.880 --> 13:09.360
At least I'll get some sleep.

13:09.360 --> 13:13.520
He found some wood in the corner of the living room and made a fire in the fireplace.

13:13.520 --> 13:16.720
He covered himself with his coat and slept.

13:16.720 --> 13:19.760
Toward morning the fire went out and the cold awakened him.

13:19.760 --> 13:25.120
It'll be light soon he thought, then I'll go for help.

13:25.120 --> 13:32.520
He closed his eyes again, but before he could doze off there was a terrible crash.

13:32.520 --> 13:36.320
Something big and heavy had fallen out of the chimney.

13:36.320 --> 13:42.480
He'd lay on the floor for a minute, then it stood up and stared down on him.

13:42.480 --> 13:45.120
The man took one look and started running.

13:45.120 --> 13:48.520
He'd never seen anything so horrible in his life.

13:48.520 --> 13:51.360
He paused just long enough to jump through a window.

13:51.360 --> 13:59.400
Then he ran and ran and ran and ran until he thought his lungs would burst.

13:59.400 --> 14:03.120
As he stood in the road panting trying to catch his breath he felt something tap him

14:03.120 --> 14:04.760
on the shoulder.

14:04.760 --> 14:11.840
He turned and found himself staring into two big bloody eyes in a grinning skull.

14:11.840 --> 14:14.520
It was a horrible thing.

14:14.520 --> 14:17.320
One of me had said, is something wrong?

14:44.520 --> 15:09.080
High beams.

15:09.080 --> 15:13.480
The girl driving the old blue sedan was a senior at the high school.

15:13.480 --> 15:19.280
She lived on a farm about eight miles away and used the car to drive back and forth.

15:19.280 --> 15:22.120
She had driven into town that night to see a baseball game.

15:22.120 --> 15:25.120
Now she was on her way home.

15:25.120 --> 15:28.800
As she pulled away from the school she noticed a red pickup truck follow her out of the parking

15:28.800 --> 15:29.800
lot.

15:29.800 --> 15:33.120
A few minutes later the truck was still behind her.

15:33.120 --> 15:38.200
I guess we're going in the same direction she thought.

15:38.200 --> 15:41.360
She began to watch the truck in her mirror.

15:41.360 --> 15:45.760
When she changed speed the driver of the truck changed his speed.

15:45.760 --> 15:50.120
When she passed a car he so did he.

15:50.120 --> 15:56.800
Then he turned on his high beams, flooding her car with light.

15:56.800 --> 15:59.880
He left them on for almost a minute.

15:59.880 --> 16:03.280
He probably wants to pass me, she thought.

16:03.280 --> 16:07.280
But she was becoming uneasy.

16:07.280 --> 16:10.280
Usually she drove home over a back road.

16:10.280 --> 16:17.800
Not too many people went that way, but when she turned onto that road so did the truck.

16:17.800 --> 16:24.800
I've got to get away from him, and she began to drive faster.

16:24.800 --> 16:28.160
Then he turned his high beams on again.

16:28.160 --> 16:35.360
After a minute he turned them off, then he turned them on again and off again.

16:35.360 --> 16:41.240
He drove even faster, but the truck stayed right behind her.

16:41.240 --> 16:44.480
Then he turned his high beams on again.

16:44.480 --> 16:49.080
Once more her car was ablaze with light, what is he doing she wondered?

16:49.080 --> 16:51.440
What does he want?

16:51.440 --> 16:53.720
Then he turned them off again.

16:53.720 --> 17:00.480
But a minute later he had them on again, and he left them on.

17:00.480 --> 17:05.640
At last she pulled into her driveway, and the truck pulled right in behind her.

17:05.640 --> 17:09.560
She jumped from the car and ran to the house, call the police!

17:09.560 --> 17:11.680
She screamed at her father.

17:11.680 --> 17:15.400
Out in the driveway she could see the driver of the truck.

17:15.400 --> 17:25.680
He had a gun in his hand.

17:25.680 --> 17:30.000
When the police arrived they started to arrest him, but he pointed to the girl's car.

17:30.000 --> 17:33.440
They don't want me, he said, you want him!

17:33.440 --> 17:40.360
Crouched behind the driver's seat, there was a man with a knife.

17:40.360 --> 17:44.080
As the driver of the truck explained it, the man slipped into the girl's car before she

17:44.080 --> 17:46.280
left the school.

17:46.280 --> 17:50.640
He saw it happen, but there was no way he could stop it.

17:50.640 --> 17:54.680
He thought about getting the police, but he was afraid to leave her, so he followed her

17:54.680 --> 17:57.280
car.

17:57.280 --> 18:01.440
Each time the man in the back seat reached up to overpower her, the driver of the truck

18:01.440 --> 18:03.840
turned on his high beams.

18:03.840 --> 18:08.840
Then the man dropped down, afraid that somebody might see him.

18:27.280 --> 18:49.040
The

18:49.040 --> 18:52.560
bed by the window.

18:52.560 --> 19:18.520
Three old men shared a room at the nursing home.

19:18.520 --> 19:24.080
The room had only one window, but for them it was the only link to the real world.

19:24.080 --> 19:29.240
Ted Conklin, who had been there the longest, had the bed next to the window.

19:29.240 --> 19:33.720
When Ted died, the man in the next bed George Best took his place, and the third man, Richard

19:33.720 --> 19:37.080
Green, took George's bed.

19:37.080 --> 19:41.400
Despite his illness, George was a cheerful man who spent his days describing the sights

19:41.400 --> 19:43.400
you could see from his bed.

19:43.400 --> 19:49.720
He grills, a policeman on horseback, a traffic jam, a pizza parlor, a fire station, and other

19:49.720 --> 19:52.400
scenes of life outside.

19:52.400 --> 19:56.160
Richard loved to listen to George, but the more George talked about life outside, the

19:56.160 --> 19:59.720
more Richard wanted to see it for himself.

19:59.720 --> 20:04.080
Yet he knew that only when George died would he have his chance.

20:04.080 --> 20:09.120
He wanted to look out that window so badly that one day he decided to kill George.

20:10.120 --> 20:15.440
He's going to die soon anyway, he told himself, what difference does it make?

20:15.440 --> 20:17.880
George had a bad heart.

20:17.880 --> 20:21.800
If he had an attack during the night and the nurse could not get to him right away, he

20:21.800 --> 20:23.920
had pills he could take.

20:23.920 --> 20:28.200
He kept them in a bottle on top of the cabinet between his bed and Richard's.

20:28.200 --> 20:34.040
All Richard had to do was knock the bottle to the floor when George could not reach it.

20:34.040 --> 20:38.680
A few nights later George died just as Richard had planned he would, and the next morning

20:38.680 --> 20:42.280
Richard was moved to the bed by the window.

20:42.280 --> 20:48.440
Now he would see for himself all the things outside that George had described.

20:48.440 --> 20:53.840
After the nurses had left, Richard turned to the window and looked out, but all he could

20:53.840 --> 20:56.920
see was a blank brick wall.

21:23.840 --> 21:50.520
I think I'm going to cry, bye bye look, I think I'm going to cry, bye bye look, bye

